Khenari cognitive discipline developed through generations of silence-court practice — the acoustic deprivation and chant-interval testimony clarification process that was designed to produce verdicts untainted by performance or social pressure. This training makes Khenari minds specifically resistant to psionicist intervention: the silence-court practice is functionally equivalent to the defensive cognitive discipline that the Pale Ledger lineage developed through deliberate research, applied to an entirely different institutional problem. In Midgaard, Khenari psionicists are unusual but not unknown: practitioners whose racial cognitive resistance gives them specific advantages in self-assessment and precision work. The more common situation is Khenari as psionicist clients: when the Temple Authority needs cognitive assessment of witnesses in contested Registry proceedings, Khenari practitioners who have submitted to assessment and then challenged the assessor's findings have produced the most technically sophisticated challenges the Midgaard Registry has encountered, because Khenari familiarity with testimony-clarification methodology gives them the vocabulary to identify assessment errors.

